item.content:encoded:
What Too Much Diet Soda Does To Your Body And Brain

Prep Time: 3 mins

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1XAgqAk1i08 Remind Risk Serving Suggestions Remind
  • When we drink diet soda, the sweetness tricks our body into thinking it’s real sugar. But when those energy-packed calories don’t arrive, the insulin has nothing to store.
  • Scientists think that repeatedly tricking our body this way could explain why study after study keeps finding the same thing: that drinking diet soda is associated with metabolic syndrome.
  • Artificial sweeteners in diet sodas can be tens to hundreds of times sweeter than sugar.
  • If the reason you’re drinking diet soda is to drop a few pounds, maybe stick to water.
Risk
  • Artificial sweeteners in diet soda can cause headaches.
  • Diet soda can cause breakouts.
  • Diet soda has been linked to depression.
  • Diet soda drinkers have a lower bone density.
  • Diet soda could interfere with your gut health.
  • Drinking diet soda increases your risk of metabolic syndrome and diabetes.
  • Diet soda mixed with alcohol makes you more intoxicated.
  • Drinking diet soda can interfere with your sense of taste.
  • Drinking diet soda puts you at high risk for hypertension.
  • Diet soda consumed by pregnant women can affect their children.
Serving Suggestions
  • Infuse Your Water With Delicious Flavor.
  • Go Natural With Green Tea, Hot or Iced.
  • Take Your Water Sparkling for That Bubbly Feeling.
  • Add Juice to Seltzer and You’ve Got.
  • Fake a Lemon-Lime Soda to Satisfy Your Citrus Fix.
  • Juice Fresh Vegetables, No Chopping Needed.
  • If You Can’t Do Dairy, Consider Soy Milk.
  • If You Need Caffeine, Have a Cup of Coffee.
  • Sip on Kombucha, a Fermented Tea.
  • Refresh With a Glass of Coconut Water.

item.title: YOU NEED TO KNOW
item.dc:creator: user
item.content:encoded:
What Too Much Diet Soda Does To Your Body And Brain

Prep Time: 3 mins

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1XAgqAk1i08 Remind Risk Serving Suggestions Remind
  • When we drink diet soda, the sweetness tricks our body into thinking it’s real sugar. But when those energy-packed calories don’t arrive, the insulin has nothing to store.
  • Scientists think that repeatedly tricking our body this way could explain why study after study keeps finding the same thing: that drinking diet soda is associated with metabolic syndrome.
  • Artificial sweeteners in diet sodas can be tens to hundreds of times sweeter than sugar.
  • If the reason you’re drinking diet soda is to drop a few pounds, maybe stick to water.
Risk
  • Artificial sweeteners in diet soda can cause headaches.
  • Diet soda can cause breakouts.
  • Diet soda has been linked to depression.
  • Diet soda drinkers have a lower bone density.
  • Diet soda could interfere with your gut health.
  • Drinking diet soda increases your risk of metabolic syndrome and diabetes.
  • Diet soda mixed with alcohol makes you more intoxicated.
  • Drinking diet soda can interfere with your sense of taste.
  • Drinking diet soda puts you at high risk for hypertension.
  • Diet soda consumed by pregnant women can affect their children.
Serving Suggestions
  • Infuse Your Water With Delicious Flavor.
  • Go Natural With Green Tea, Hot or Iced.
  • Take Your Water Sparkling for That Bubbly Feeling.
  • Add Juice to Seltzer and You’ve Got.
  • Fake a Lemon-Lime Soda to Satisfy Your Citrus Fix.
  • Juice Fresh Vegetables, No Chopping Needed.
  • If You Can’t Do Dairy, Consider Soy Milk.
  • If You Need Caffeine, Have a Cup of Coffee.
  • Sip on Kombucha, a Fermented Tea.
  • Refresh With a Glass of Coconut Water.

item.title: Privacy Policy
item.dc:creator: user
item.content:encoded:
Who we are

Suggested text: Our website address is: http://127.0.0.1.

Comments

Suggested text: When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor’s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.

An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.

Media

Suggested text: If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.

Cookies

Suggested text: If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.

If you visit our login page, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.

When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select "Remember Me", your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.

If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.

Embedded content from other websites

Suggested text: Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.

These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.

Who we share your data with

Suggested text: If you request a password reset, your IP address will be included in the reset email.

How long we retain your data

Suggested text: If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.

For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.

What rights you have over your data

Suggested text: If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.

Where your data is sent

Suggested text: Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.

item.title: HealNews
item.dc:creator: user
item.content:encoded:
You may want to learn more about soft drinks for your health!
Here are the latest news and publications related to drinks!

What If We Drank COLA Everday?

Prep Time: 5 mins

https://youtu.be/do1lP632bY8 Remind Risk Serving Suggestions Remind
  • Soft drink consumption has increased substantially over the last 50 years and it has been established that people have large amounts of soft drinks regularly. Caffeine is a stimulant that is found in soft drinks. In large amounts can have detrimental effects on your health, Today we bring you the eight cons of it.
Risk
  • You tend to consume more total calories if you drink soda, as liquid sugar doesn’t make you feel full. Sugar-sweetened beverages are associated with weight gain.
  • Sugary soda may cause insulin resistance — a key feature of metabolic syndrome.
  • Sugar-sweetened beverages may be the leading dietary cause of type 2 diabetes.
  • Sugary sodas contain little to no essential nutrients, only providing sugar and calories.
  • Sugary drinks have powerful effects on your brain’s reward system, which may lead to addiction.
  • Soda drinkers have a higher risk of cancer.
  • The acids in soda create an acidic environment in your mouth, while the sugar feeds the harmful bacteria that reside there. This can have severe adverse effects on dental health.
  • Soda drinkers have a drastically increased risk of gout.
Serving Suggestions
  • Infuse Your Water With Delicious Flavor.
  • Go Natural With Green Tea, Hot or Iced.
  • Take Your Water Sparkling for That Bubbly Feeling.
  • Add Juice to Seltzer and You’ve Got.
  • Fake a Lemon-Lime Soda to Satisfy Your Citrus Fix.
  • Juice Fresh Vegetables, No Chopping Needed.
  • If You Can’t Do Dairy, Consider Soy Milk.
  • If You Need Caffeine, Have a Cup of Coffee.
  • Sip on Kombucha, a Fermented Tea.
  • Refresh With a Glass of Coconut Water.

You might be interested with more information about drinking!

Healthy Drink Recipes

Make your own nutritious smoothies, hot beverages and mocktails. From an on-trend turmeric latte to herbal tea and almond milk, these healthier drinks are full of flavour.

Read More
10 Healthy Drinks You’re Not Drinking—Yet!

Sure, water is the smartest drink out there, but if you're craving something more, these healthy drinks will give you a boost of nutrition.

Read More
Diet Soda Health Risks and Facts That Might Make You Finally Stop Drinking It

Many diet sodas are sweetened with aspartame, an artificial sweetener that is sweeter than sugar. New flavours of Diet Coke first released in 2018 are sweetened with “Ace-K,” a controversial sweetener that tastes 200 times sweeter than regular refined sugar.

Read More

Join Hundreds of Healthy People

COLLECT Our Page TODAY & GET More Information About the Carbonated Drinks in Your Body!

    • You tend to consume more total calories if you drink soda, as liquid sugar doesn\u2019t make you feel full. Sugar-sweetened beverages are associated with weight gain.<\/li>
    • Sugary soda may cause insulin resistance \u2014 a key feature of metabolic syndrome.<\/li>
    • Sugar-sweetened beverages may be the leading dietary cause of type 2 diabetes.<\/li>
    • Sugary sodas contain little to no essential nutrients, only providing sugar and calories.<\/li>
    • Sugary drinks have powerful effects on your brain\u2019s reward system, which may lead to addiction.<\/li>
    • Soda drinkers have a higher risk of cancer.<\/li>
    • The acids in soda create an acidic environment in your mouth, while the sugar feeds the harmful bacteria that reside there. This can have severe adverse effects on dental health.<\/li>

item.title: Privacy Policy
item.dc:creator: user
item.content:encoded:
Who we are

Suggested text: Our website address is: https://healdrink.tk/

Comments

Suggested text: When visitors leave comments on the site we collect the data shown in the comments form, and also the visitor’s IP address and browser user agent string to help spam detection.

An anonymized string created from your email address (also called a hash) may be provided to the Gravatar service to see if you are using it. The Gravatar service privacy policy is available here: https://automattic.com/privacy/. After approval of your comment, your profile picture is visible to the public in the context of your comment.

Media

Suggested text: If you upload images to the website, you should avoid uploading images with embedded location data (EXIF GPS) included. Visitors to the website can download and extract any location data from images on the website.

Cookies

Suggested text: If you leave a comment on our site you may opt-in to saving your name, email address and website in cookies. These are for your convenience so that you do not have to fill in your details again when you leave another comment. These cookies will last for one year.

If you visit our login page, we will set a temporary cookie to determine if your browser accepts cookies. This cookie contains no personal data and is discarded when you close your browser.

When you log in, we will also set up several cookies to save your login information and your screen display choices. Login cookies last for two days, and screen options cookies last for a year. If you select "Remember Me", your login will persist for two weeks. If you log out of your account, the login cookies will be removed.

If you edit or publish an article, an additional cookie will be saved in your browser. This cookie includes no personal data and simply indicates the post ID of the article you just edited. It expires after 1 day.

Embedded content from other websites

Suggested text: Articles on this site may include embedded content (e.g. videos, images, articles, etc.). Embedded content from other websites behaves in the exact same way as if the visitor has visited the other website.

These websites may collect data about you, use cookies, embed additional third-party tracking, and monitor your interaction with that embedded content, including tracking your interaction with the embedded content if you have an account and are logged in to that website.

Who we share your data with

Suggested text: If you request a password reset, your IP address will be included in the reset email.

How long we retain your data

Suggested text: If you leave a comment, the comment and its metadata are retained indefinitely. This is so we can recognize and approve any follow-up comments automatically instead of holding them in a moderation queue.

For users that register on our website (if any), we also store the personal information they provide in their user profile. All users can see, edit, or delete their personal information at any time (except they cannot change their username). Website administrators can also see and edit that information.

What rights you have over your data

Suggested text: If you have an account on this site, or have left comments, you can request to receive an exported file of the personal data we hold about you, including any data you have provided to us. You can also request that we erase any personal data we hold about you. This does not include any data we are obliged to keep for administrative, legal, or security purposes.

Where your data is sent

Suggested text: Visitor comments may be checked through an automated spam detection service.

Coffee

If You Need Caffeine, Have a Cup of Coffee - Unsweetened coffee, either black or with a small amount of nonfat or low-fat milk, or plant-based milk like almond or soy would be the healthiest option.

Kombucha

Kombucha, A Fermented Tea - if you’re sensitive to the effects of alcohol or if you’re pregnant or nursing, KEEP IN MIND that a small amount of alcohol is produced by the fermentation process.

Soy Milk

If You Can't Do Dairy, Consider Soy Milk - People who are lactose intolerant or who don't consume dairy, soy milk can be a good protein-packed, plant-based alternative, available in a variety of flavors, including almond and vanilla.

Green tea

Go Natural With Green Tea, Hot or Iced - Green tea is calorie-free (if you have it without milk or sugar) and naturally high in antioxidants. Green tea is available in many varieties. Drink it hot or iced.
